====================================================================
üìå RELATIONSHIPS IN DBMS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

A Relationship in DBMS defines HOW two or more tables/entities
are connected to each other.

Relationships are created using **KEYS** (Primary Key & Foreign Key).

====================================================================
WHY DO WE USE RELATIONSHIPS ?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî To connect related data from different tables  
‚úî To avoid data duplication  
‚úî To maintain data integrity  
‚úî To represent real-world connections  
‚úî To enable meaningful queries using JOIN  

====================================================================
TYPES OF RELATIONSHIPS IN DBMS
--------------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£ One-to-One (1:1)  
2Ô∏è‚É£ One-to-Many (1:M)  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Many-to-One (M:1)  
4Ô∏è‚É£ Many-to-Many (M:M)    

====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£ ONE-TO-ONE RELATIONSHIP (1:1)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
One record in Table A is related to ONLY ONE record in Table B.

Example:
PERSON ‚Üî PASSPORT  

PERSON table:
person_id (PK)

PASSPORT table:
passport_id (PK)
person_id (FK)

USE:
‚úî When extra information is optional  
‚úî Security-related data  

====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ ONE-TO-MANY RELATIONSHIP (1:M)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
One record in Table A can be related to MANY records in Table B,
but Table B record relates to ONLY ONE record in Table A.

Example:
DEPARTMENT ‚Üí EMPLOYEE  

DEPARTMENT table:
dept_id (PK)

EMPLOYEE table:
emp_id (PK)
dept_id (FK)

USE:
‚úî Most common relationship  
‚úî Parent-child data  

====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ MANY-TO-ONE RELATIONSHIP (M:1)  
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Many records in Table A are related to ONE record in Table B.

Example:
EMPLOYEE ‚Üí DEPARTMENT  

NOTE:
‚úî This is the reverse view of One-to-Many  

====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ MANY-TO-MANY RELATIONSHIP (M:M)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Many records in Table A are related to MANY records in Table B.

Example:
STUDENT ‚Üî COURSE  

IMPLEMENTATION:
‚úî Requires a JUNCTION TABLE  

STUDENT_COURSE table:
student_id (FK)
course_id (FK)

USE:
‚úî Real-world scenarios  
‚úî Complex relationships  

====================================================================
RELATIONSHIP USING KEYS
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Primary Key (PK) ‚Üí Unique identifier  
‚úî Foreign Key (FK) ‚Üí References PK of another table  

Example:
EMPLOYEE.dept_id ‚Üí DEPARTMENT.dept_id  

====================================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî User ‚Üí Orders (1:M)  
‚úî Country ‚Üí Cities (1:M)  
‚úî Student ‚Üî Subject (M:M)  
‚úî Person ‚Üî Aadhaar (1:1)  

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================

‚úî Relationships connect tables  
‚úî Foreign Key creates relationship  
‚úî One-to-Many is most common  
‚úî Many-to-Many needs a junction table  
‚úî Relationships ensure data integrity  

END OF NOTES
